    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-03-18T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-03-18T13:00:00-05:00" n="70"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d70">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">641.6231/178: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-03-18T18:00:00+00:00"
                            >March 18, 1939—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 18—2:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>364. Your 169, March 7, 6 p.m.<note n="27" xml:id="d70fn27">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_28">p. 28</ref>.</note>
                    Bracken, editor of <hi rend="italic">Financial News</hi>, London, makes
                    statement that Sir Walter Layton<note n="28" xml:id="d70fn28">Chairman, News
                        Chronicle, Ltd., and Star Newspaper Co., Ltd., London.</note> who has just
                    returned from the United States, asserts you are seriously perturbed as to the
                    possible course of the current Federation of British Industries–Reichsgruppe
                    Industrie trade negotiations.</p>
                <p>Wallace, representative of Chase Bank here, tells Oliver Stanley<note n="29"
                        xml:id="d70fn29">President of the British Board of Trade.</note> that
                        Aldridge<note n="30" xml:id="d70fn30">Apparently refers to Winthrop W.
                        Aldrich, Chairman of the Board of the Chase National Bank.</note> reports
                    you as approving these negotiations. Stanley and Board of Trade concerned about
                    these contrary reports. Although information as to actual results achieved to
                    date is not yet available, I would appreciate receiving some definite statement
                    to give Stanley.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
